04208nam a22005655i 9780822383895DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223838957 a10.1515/97808223838952doi  a(DE-B1597)553741  a(OCoLC)1159326089  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ781b.C37 2002 7aSOC0470002bisacsh1 aCastañeda, Claudia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFigurations :bChild, Bodies, Worlds /cClaudia Castañeda; Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan, Inderpal Grewal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Figurations: Child, Bodies, Worlds -- t1. Developmentalism and the Child in Nineteenth-Century Science -- t2 Flexible Child-Bodies -- t3 Available Childhood: Race, Culture, and the Transnational Adoptee -- t4 Rumored Realities: Child-Organ Theft -- t5 The Child, in Theory: Post-structuralism, Feminism, and Psychoanalysis -- tNotes -- tReference List -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlways in the process of becoming, inherently incomplete, the child is a remarkably malleable figure. In Figurations, Claudia Castañeda shows how this malleability is itself generated-how the child is "made" by different constituencies and how the resulting historically, geographically, and culturally specific figures are put to widely divergent uses, often to very powerful effect. Situated at the intersection of feminist, postcolonial, cultural, and science and technology studies, this book provides a remarkable map of the child's meaning and movement across transnational circuits of exchange.Castañeda investigates the construction of the child as both a natural and cultural body, the character of its embodiment, and its imaginative appeal in various settings. The sites through which she tracks the bodily production and deployment of the child include nineteenth-century developmental science; cognitive neuroscience in the late twentieth century; international adoption; rumors and media coverage of child-organ stealing; and poststructuralist theory. Her work reveals the extent to which the child's cultural significance and value lie in its status as a body whose incompleteness makes it "available" for such varied uses. Figurations establishes the child as a key figure for understanding and rethinking the politics of nature, culture, bodies, and subjects in changing "global" worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aChildren. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aGrewal, Inderpal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383895zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383895423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822383895.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles